25|$|As {{the country}} entered 1976, the socialist {{alliance}} of Bhutto collapsed, forcing his left-wing allies {{to form an}} alliance with right-wing conservatives and <b>Islamists</b> to challenge {{the power of the}} PPP. The <b>Islamists</b> started a Nizam-e-Mustafa movement which demanded the establishment of an Islamic state in the country and removal of immorality from society. In an effort {{to meet the demands of}} <b>Islamists,</b> Bhutto banned the drinking and selling of wine by Muslims and also banned nightclubs and horse racing.|$|R
